<TEXT type="str">Frequent contributors to editorial pages remind us that we, and other world constituencies, have developed populistic views that favor nationalism and anti-globalization. What no one asks, however, is whether those views are good for the country, or even if they are good for voters anywhere. 
   
The pundits all say, “Well, that’s what people are thinking.” They then speculate endlessly about how the change will affect policies, institutions and actions that emerged before all these “new” ideas blossomed. But again, no one asks whether the nationalistic, anti-globalization attitudes are healthy, beneficial, promising or even sensible? Is it really good to promote “me-only” or “we-only” policies and actions? 
   
