However humans have gotten to inhabit this earth, living together favors working in community rather than working as isolates. Hunters and gatherers survived more when groups cooperated in harvesting food. Are we, a far more technologically and socially integrated civilization, any different? Absolutely not. No human is born and survives without the extended help of other caregivers. And no group of humans today survives without the benefit of handed-down traditions regarding food, clothing, housing, medicines, tools, or ultimately without the benefit of viable social institutions like families, schools, employers, networks and even entertainers. 
   
So is trending toward isolationism and against open commerce a good idea? Not at all. We need to shout more clearly the benefits of cooperation and coexistence rather than simply accepting “we-only” trends that are detrimental in the long run. - Herb Kuehne, Sioux City</TEXT> 
